<DIV id=3Dwiki>In <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?ExtremeProgramming">ExtremeProgramming</A>=
 a <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStory">UserStory</A> is a story about =
how the=20
system is supposed to solve a problem or support a business process. =
Each <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStory">UserStory</A> is written on a =
<A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?StoryCard">StoryCard</A>, and represents =
a chunk of=20
functionality that is coherent in some way to the customer. [?]=20
<P></P>These written cards are preserved through the entire planning and =

development process (<A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?PlanningGame">PlanningGame</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?ReleasePlan">ReleasePlan</A>, <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?IterationPlanning">IterationPlanning</A>).=
 They are=20
given priorities by the customers, they are given estimates by the =
developers,=20
they are broken down into <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?EngineeringTask">EngineeringTask</A><STRON=
G></STRONG>s=20
at the time that they are scheduled for development. There are one or =
more <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?AcceptanceTest">AcceptanceTest</A><STRONG>=
</STRONG>s,=20
owned by the customers, to give them confidence that the <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStory">UserStory</A> has actually =
been=20
completed.=20
