<P></P>Now that I've read a little more and asked a few more questions =
I'm=20
getting a view of a <A =
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStory">UserStory</A>=20
that's more involved than what's been presented on this page so far. =
<STRONG>A=20
<A href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStory">UserStory</A> is also a =
work unit and=20
an estimation unit. In this it's actually considerably heavier - not =
lighter -=20
than a <A href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UseCase">UseCase</A>.</STRONG> =
A <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStory">UserStory</A> as an estimation =
unit is=20
inadequate if it can't be properly quantified in the <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?PlanningGame">PlanningGame</A>. A <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStory">UserStory</A> as a work unit =
is=20
inadequate if it isn't split up into <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?EngineeringTask">EngineeringTask</A><STRON=
G></STRONG>s,=20
each of which must be properly regression tested and refactored to make =
the=20
simplest 100% working system. Oh, and as a work unit it has to have an=20
acceptance test too. So <A =
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStory">UserStory</A>=20
is a word with considerable process baggage in XP, not just a 2-bit <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UseCase">UseCase</A>.=20
<P></P>So I have a question about the thing as an estimation unit. <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?EngineeringTask">EngineeringTask</A><STRON=
G></STRONG>s,=20
we're told, have to be able to be estimated as no more than 5, and =
preferably=20
less than 3 ideal engineering days. <STRONG>Is there a similar criterion =
for a=20
<A href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStory">UserStory</A>?</STRONG> -- =
<A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?PeterMerel">PeterMerel</A>=20
<P></P><STRONG>From <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?RonJeffries">RonJeffries</A>:</STRONG> In =
<A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?CommitmentSchedule">CommitmentSchedule</A>=
, we ask=20
the users to split a story if we estimate it at more than about 3 weeks, =
on the=20
grounds that we don't understand it. We combine stories willy-nilly if =
they=20
don't add up to at least a week, for estimation only. (That is, we don't =
intend=20
to implement them in that order, we just batch them up in piles of a =
week.)=20
<P></P><STRONG>From <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?KentBeck">KentBeck</A>:</STRONG> Remember =
also that=20
the role of a story as a work unit comes considerably after the role of =
a story=20
as a priority/scope decision unit (for which it also needs to be an =
estimation=20
unit).=20
<P></P>I was trying to use your words. I'll try again. The story is used =
by the=20
customer to make informed decisions about the scope of the next release, =

decisions informed by the estimated cost of the story and the velocity =
with=20
which the team can develop. When the story's iteration rolls around, it =
becomes=20
a work unit by being split into tasks (or not on smaller developments) =
and a=20
test unit by being coded as a bunch of acceptance tests.=20
<P></P>The stories are really the artifact at the heart of the =
continuing dialog=20
between what is possible and what is desirable. -- <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?KentBeck">KentBeck</A>=20
<P></P>Which is exactly as it should be in my humble opinion, and one of =
the=20
most attractive features in XP. Other "OO" methodologies are not really =
OO;=20
they're work/data flows. Specifications become Analysis becomes Design =
becomes=20
Code becomes Deliverables become Tests become Deployed Systems. XP says =
to me,=20
lookit, this thing you're asking for is what we're estimating and what =
we're=20
estimating is what we're doing and what we're testing and what we're =
maintaining=20
and delivering - they're all just methods on this one thing, "User =
Story". Or=20
maybe I'm going off the deep end, but that's how it seems to me.=20
<P></P>I should say that I'm in a bizarre methodological context at the =
moment;=20
trying to relate XP concepts to RUP and MSF concepts without doing =
violence to=20
any of 'em on behalf of a certain very large company who shall remain =
nameless=20
for now. So my perspective is skewed and I may be quite mad - please =
deal=20
harshly with me. -- <A =
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?PeterMerel">PeterMerel</A>=20
