know things like what is the mutex behaviour, is it ISR safe, what is =
the max=20
amount of memory that can be used, what's the on disk limit, etc. Is =
each of=20
these a separate story or part of the same story?=20
<HR>

<P></P>That's an interesting paradigm, it's a practical method to =
developing.=20
But my questions are about the maintenance of that system when the team =
work has=20
been dissolved. I mean, are the <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStories">UserStories</A> enough to =
understand=20
the code, and the programming philosophy?; could other work team take =
the=20
administration or maintenance of that system? HOW? -- <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?LucasZallio">LucasZallio</A>=20
<P></P>
<HR>

<P></P>What happened to user stories? They seem to be morphing into =
requirements=20
and use cases. I read now where they have turn into an acceptance test =
which=20
really requires an immense amount of detail. For example, i can't just =
have a=20
short story like "user can select shipping options" and then talk about =
what=20
that means later. For a test to be generated this would have to be fully =

designed into a form that is much larger than any index card and would =
be more=20
complete than the heaviest use case.=20
<HR>
I thought I had this all figured out; now you all have me confused.=20
<P></P>I've been using <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UserStories">UserStories</A> as concrete =
examples=20
of <A href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?UseCases">UseCases</A> being =
invoked. Most of=20
the requirements negotiation tends to fall not in the general =
characteristics of=20
a use case but in the detail revealed in a user story (The who, what, =
why of a=20
use case usually is pretty much determined by the business process).=20
<P></P>What I find disturbing in this discussion is the suggestion that =
there is=20
some deep gulf between them. I learned a long time ago that the most =
useful use=20
case is:=20
<P></P>
<UL>
  <LI>a unit of interaction; you can imagine the user coming up to the =
machine,=20
  invoking a use case, and walking away happy.=20
  <LI>a unit of work; it can be delivered in one iteration and =
cost-estimated=20
  with some confidence.=20
  <LI>a unit of test.=20
  <LI>a unit of documentation.=20
  <LI>one section in the user guide.=20
  <LI>one help frame.=20
  <P></P></LI></UL>This sounds pretty close to the specs for a user =
story. -- <A=20
href=3D"http://c2.com/cgi/wiki?MarcThibault">MarcThibault</A>=20
<HR>
By Mohammed Qattan:=20
<P></P>As a matter of fact, user stories are something that I cannot =
really=20
describe how they made my life easier. Here is what I did. My company is =
PMI=20
standards oriented, so they still believe in plans, schedules and dead =
lines.=20
And in order to get the contract, I had to submit a full detailed plan. =
This=20
cannot happen, this is why XP is for. Not to give deadlines that you =
really=20
don't know about well, in the plans I used to give about 2-3 weeks of an =
item=20
called "User Stories and Interface" it was a good sell for them (both my =
CEO and=20
the Customer). What I did is that I used to meet with the customer, and =
I did=20
write the user stories. And I changed the Metaphor concept a bit for =
each user=20
story I had a page as a prototype and when user stories are complete =
into a=20
scene I rushed back to the customer to get their feedback on the =
prototype and=20
from the user stories I had tasks. I am a project manager, and I am not =
away=20
from the code, so I meet with the developers, and we estimate on the =
user=20
stories, and I make sure to down size the tasks to a day for each now I =
have a=20
plan according to the PMI standards and in fact I am doing the iteration =

according to the XP and I have a milestone (a release) and I had the =
developers=20
estimate and each developer can come to my office to get his/her user =
story, and=20
with the user story there is an attached document representing the page =
from the=20
prototype. All what I know is the pile of user stories is vanishing in =
the speed=20
of light. I really love XP and I really owe a big thank you for the =
great people=20
who made my life happy - the people who invented this XP.=20
